Map for Pop Density in East Africa in 2025

# Load the libraries
library(R.utils)
library(dplyr)
library(sf)
library(ggplot2)
library(tmap)
library(viridis)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(raster)
library(terra)
library(exactextractr)
library(tidyterra)
library(ggspatial)
library(classInt)

# Read the population density raster files for 2025
raster_2025 <- raster("M:/gds/assn/data/pop/global_pop_2025_CN_1km_R2025A_UA_v1.tif")

# Convert to terra object (rast)
raster_2025_terra <- rast(raster_2025)

# Read the shapefiles for African countries (administrative boundaries)
admin0_shapefile <- st_read("M:/gds/assn/data/admin0/Countries.shp")
admin1_shapefile <- st_read("M:/gds/assn/data/admin1/afr_g2014_2013_1_update.shp")

# Select Countries with shapefile
countries <- c("Kenya","Somalia","Ethiopia","Uganda","Tanzania","Democratic Republic of the Congo","South Sudan")

# Reproject the raster to UTM Zone 37N (EPSG:32637)
raster_2025_utm <- project(raster_2025_terra, "EPSG:32637")

# Reproject the admin0 and admin1 shapefiles to UTM Zone 37N (EPSG:32637)
admin0_shapefile_utm <- st_transform(admin0_shapefile, crs = 32637)
admin1_shapefile_utm <- st_transform(admin1_shapefile, crs = 32637)

# Clip the raster data by the selected countries
countries <- admin0_shapefile_utm %>%
  filter(ADM0_NAME %in% countries)

raster_2025_clipped <- mask(raster_2025_utm, countries)
saveRDS(raster_2025_clipped, "raster_2025_clipped.rds")

# Keep the district boundaries (Admin1) that intersect the country
admin1_shapefile_utm <- st_make_valid(admin1_shapefile_utm)
countries <- st_make_valid(countries)
district_boundary <- st_intersection(admin1_shapefile_utm, countries)
district_boundary <- st_make_valid(district_boundary)

# Keep only POLYGON or MULTIPOLYGON types and non-zero area
district_boundary <- district_boundary %>%
  st_make_valid() %>%   # fix invalid geometries
  filter(st_geometry_type(.) %in% c("POLYGON", "MULTIPOLYGON", "GEOMETRYCOLLECTION")) %>%  # keep relevant types
  filter(as.numeric(st_area(.)) > 0)  # remove degenerate polygons

district_boundary <- st_collection_extract(district_boundary, "POLYGON")

# Calculate mean population density within each district
pop_density_2025_district <- exact_extract(raster_2025_clipped, district_boundary, 'mean')

# Add the results back to the district polygons
district_boundary$pop_density_2025 <- pop_density_2025_district
# Replace NA with 0
district_boundary <- district_boundary %>%
  filter(!is.na(pop_density_2025) & pop_density_2025 > 0)

# Calculate centroids for labeling
countries_centroids <- st_centroid(countries)

# Create quantile breaks
n_classes <- 5
breaks <- quantile(
  district_boundary$pop_density_2025,
  probs = seq(0, 1, length.out = n_classes + 1),
  na.rm = TRUE
)

# Make breaks unique and rounded
breaks <- unique(round(breaks, 2))

# Assign bins
district_boundary <- district_boundary %>%
  mutate(pop_density_class = cut(
    pop_density_2025,
    breaks = breaks,
    include.lowest = TRUE
  ))

# --- Create Map Plot ---
map_plot <- ggplot() +
  annotation_map_tile(type = "cartolight", zoom = 8) +
  geom_sf(
    data = district_boundary,
    aes(fill = pop_density_class),
    color = "grey20",
    size = 0.3,
    alpha = 0.9
  ) +
  geom_sf(data = countries, fill = NA, color = "black", linewidth = 0.5) +
  geom_sf_text(
    data = st_centroid(countries),
    aes(label = ADM0_NAME),
    size = 4,
    fontface = "bold",
    color = "white"
  ) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "YlOrRd",
  name = "Population Density (2025)",
  na.value = NA
  ) +
  coord_sf() +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  labs(
    title = "Population Density Across East Africa (2025)"
  ) +
  theme(
    legend.position = "right",
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "transparent")
  )

print(map_plot)

Map for Population density change from 2015 to 2025 for East Africa

# Load the libraries
library(R.utils)
library(dplyr)
library(sf)
library(ggplot2)
library(tmap)
library(viridis)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(raster)
library(terra)
library(exactextractr)
library(tidyterra)
library(ggspatial)

# Read the population density raster files for 2015 and 2025
raster_2015 <- raster("M:/gds/assn/data/pop/global_pop_2015_CN_1km_R2025A_UA_v1.tif")

# Convert to terra object (rast)
raster_2015_terra <- rast(raster_2015)

# Read the shapefiles for African countries (administrative boundaries)
admin0_shapefile <- st_read("M:/gds/assn/data/admin0/Countries.shp")
admin1_shapefile <- st_read("M:/gds/assn/data/admin1/afr_g2014_2013_1_update.shp")

# Select Countries with shapefile
countries <- c("Kenya","Somalia","Ethiopia","Uganda","Tanzania","Democratic Republic of the Congo","South Sudan")

# Reproject the raster to UTM Zone 37N (EPSG:32637)
raster_2015_utm <- project(raster_2015_terra, "EPSG:32637")

# Reproject the admin0 and admin1 shapefiles to UTM Zone 37N (EPSG:32637)
admin0_shapefile_utm <- st_transform(admin0_shapefile, crs = 32637)
admin1_shapefile_utm <- st_transform(admin1_shapefile, crs = 32637)

# Clip the raster data by the selected countries
countries <- admin0_shapefile_utm %>%
  filter(ADM0_NAME %in% countries)

raster_2015_clipped <- mask(raster_2015_utm, countries)
raster_2025_clipped <- readRDS("raster_2025_clipped.rds")

# MUP and hex bins
hex_grid <- st_make_grid(countries, cellsize = 45000, what = "polygons", square = FALSE)

# Convert hexagonal grid to raster
hex_grid_spat <- vect(hex_grid)
hex_grid_raster <- rasterize(hex_grid_spat, raster_2015_clipped, field = 1, background = NA)

# Calculate the zonal statistics (mean population density in each hexagon)
pop_density_2015 <- extract(raster_2015_clipped, hex_grid_spat, fun = mean, na.rm = TRUE)
pop_density_2025 <- extract(raster_2025_clipped, hex_grid_spat, fun = mean, na.rm = TRUE)

# Add pop density values back to hex polygons
hex_grid_sf <- st_as_sf(hex_grid)
hex_grid_sf$pop_density_2015 <- as.numeric(pop_density_2015[[2]])
hex_grid_sf$pop_density_2025 <- as.numeric(pop_density_2025[[2]])

# Replace NAN with 0 values
hex_grid_sf$pop_density_2015[is.nan(hex_grid_sf$pop_density_2015)] <- 0
hex_grid_sf$pop_density_2025[is.nan(hex_grid_sf$pop_density_2025)] <- 0

# Add pop density values back to hex polygons
# Clip hex grid to countries boundary
hex_grid_sf <- st_intersection(hex_grid_sf, countries)

# Ensure valid geometries before intersection
admin1_shapefile_utm <- st_make_valid(admin1_shapefile_utm)
countries <- st_make_valid(countries)

# Now perform intersection safely
district_boundary <- st_intersection(admin1_shapefile_utm, countries)

# Keep only Admin1 polygons that intersect
district_boundary <- st_intersection(admin1_shapefile_utm, countries)

# Calculate Population change over 10 years
hex_grid_sf <- hex_grid_sf %>%
  mutate(
    pop_change = pop_density_2025 - pop_density_2015,
    pop_change_pct = ifelse(pop_density_2015 == 0, 
                            NA, 
                            (pop_density_2025 - pop_density_2015) / pop_density_2015 * 100)
  )

# Categorize into growth levels
# Define quantile breaks
hex_non_na <- hex_grid_sf %>% filter(!is.na(pop_change_pct))
quantiles <- quantile(hex_non_na$pop_change_pct, probs = seq(0, 1, length.out = 6), na.rm = TRUE)

# Assign growth categories based on quantiles
hex_grid_sf <- hex_grid_sf %>%
  mutate(
    growth_category = case_when(
      is.na(pop_change_pct) ~ "No Data",
      pop_change_pct <= quantiles[2] ~ "High Decline",
      pop_change_pct <= quantiles[3] ~ "Low Decline",
      pop_change_pct <= quantiles[4] ~ "Stable",
      pop_change_pct <= quantiles[5] ~ "Medium Growth",
      pop_change_pct > quantiles[5] ~ "High Growth"
    )
  )

# Define colors for growth categories
growth_colors <- c(
  "High Growth" = "#1a9850",   
  "Medium Growth" = "#66bd63", 
  "Stable" = "#fdae61",        
  "Low Decline" = "#f46d43",   
  "High Decline" = "#d73027",  
  "No Data" = "#cccccc"        
)

# Plot Map 

map_plot <- ggplot() +
  # Basemap
  annotation_map_tile(type = "cartolight", zoom = 8) +
  
  # Hex grid choropleth
  geom_sf(data = hex_grid_sf, aes(fill = growth_category), color = "grey20", size = 0.2) +
  
  # Country boundaries overlay
  geom_sf(data = countries, fill = NA, color = "black", size = 0.3) +
  
  # Optional: Add country labels
  geom_sf_text(
    data = st_centroid(countries),
    aes(label = ADM0_NAME),
    size = 4,
    fontface = "bold",
    color = "white"
  ) +
  
  # Colors
  scale_fill_manual(values = growth_colors, name = "Population Growth\n(2015â2025)") +
  
  # Titles and theme
  labs(
    title = "Population Growth in East Africa (2015â2025)",
    subtitle = "Based on mean population density in hexagonal grids"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "right",
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "transparent")
  )

# Display combined plot
print(map_plot)
# Plot Histogram
pop_change_data <- hex_grid_sf %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%  
  filter(!is.na(pop_change_pct))

hist_plot <- ggplot(pop_change_data, aes(x = pop_change_pct)) +
  geom_histogram(
    bins = 30, 
    fill = "#66c2a5", 
    color = "black", 
    alpha = 0.8
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Population Change (2015â2025)",
    x = "Population Change (%)",
    y = "Number of Hexagons"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12)
  )

print(hist_plot)

Explanation (Story)

  1. What value is associated with each pixel?

    The raster data downloaded for world population has a value of each pixel. The value associated with each pixel is the population density in every 1 km resolution in the world. The population density the number of people per square km (1km resolution). It can be considered as a point geometry which has a value all over the world, however it is not continuous but discrete.

  2. Which CRS are you using? Justify your answer.

    The geometric coordinates of the raster data are converted to projected coordinate system UTM Zone 37N (EPSG:32637). This system is used for the East Africa region based on the geometric coordinates (in degrees). All shapefiles and tif files are projected to this system to get proper relay over layers.

  3. What is Map 1 saying about population density in East Africa?

    The first map is created using the mean of population density at district level which is admin1 boundaries of Africa. All the raster data falling within the district boundary is aggregated to mean and then reassigned to the district polygon. The quantile is used define breaks in the distribution after assigning it to the district polygons and the choropleth map is created by mapping color values to the range of data lying in the divided sections by quantile. The mean population density for the East Africa region is 122 per square km with max population density being 8880 in the Kampala district of country Uganda.. The population density is higher in regions like Uganda, Democratic Republic of Congo in comparison to Somalia, Kenya and South Sudan.

  4. Which categorical divisions (Decline, Neutral, Growth and High Growth) did you chose for Map 2 and why?

    The second map is created after calculating mean population density at hexagonal grid level. The size of the hex grid is chosen as 45000 and all the raster data falling in that hexagonal is aggregated as mean value. This is done to solve for Modifiable Areal Unit Problem (MAUP) in geographic data science where the boundaries are random. After the mean is calculated a metric called percentage growth in mean population is derived to categorize the distribution from 2015 to 2025. The breaks or categories are defined using quantile of the distribution to achieve a more balanced classification scheme. There are 5 categorical divisions based on percentage growth of population density i.e.Â High Decline, Low Decline, Stable, Medium Growth, High Growth. The mean population density for East Africa region increased from 76 per square km in 2015 to 101 per square km in 2025 which means there has been growth in population density over last 10 years overall. There are some countries like Uganda and Democratic Republic of Congo which showed higher growth in comparison to other countries like South Sudan and Kenya. The country with most decline in population density appears to be South Sudan. This leaves us with a thought that though Uganda and Democratic Republic of Congo had moderately high population density even in year 2015 and have seen growth over 10 years but Somalia stands out as a country which did not have much population in 2015 but has shown rapid growth over 10 years. South Sudan had very similar population density like Somalia in 2015 but has shown de-growth over 10 years which might be due to living conditions being scarce or unstability.
